author: Will_Marshall;
title: The mission to create a searchable database of Earth's surface

aws-transcripts.transcript: four years ago here at Ted, I announced planets Mission one to launch a fleet of satellites that would image the entire earth every day and to democratize access to it. The problem we were trying to. It's over. Simple satellite imagery you find online is old, typically years old. Yet human activity was happening on days and weeks and months. And you can't fix what you can't see. We wanted to give people the tools to see that change, to take action. The beautiful blue marble image taken by the Apollo 17 nationals in 1972 had helped humanity become aware that we're in a fragile planet. And we want to take it to the next level to give you all the tools to take action to take care of it. Well, after many Apollo Project of our own launching the largest fleet of satellites in human history, we've reached our target today. Planet images the entire earth every single day. Mission accomplished. Thank you. Uh, it's taken 21 rocket launches. This animation makes it look really simple. It was not, and we now have over 200 satellites in orbit downing in their date of the 31 ground stations we built around the planet. In total, we get one point 5,000,029 megapixel images of the earth down each day and on any one location on the Earth's surface, we now have, on average, more than 500 images. A deep stack of data documenting immense change on lots of people are using this imagery. Agricultural companies are using it to improve farmer's crop yields consumer mapping companies, using it to improve the map to find online.
